{
  "answer": "**The passage appears in *Bang-E-Dara Part 2* by Allama Iqbal, Chapter 9 (\"Chaand aur Taare\").**[^1]\n\nIn this poem, the stars complain to the moon about their weariness from eternally shining bright.[^2] The moon's full reply on motion and stillness reads:\n\n> The life of this world is in Motion's sway;  \n> It is the old, eternal way.  \n> The steed of Time runs, ever fleet,  \n> Stung by the lash of longing's beat.  \n> To pause upon this path is but a flaw,  \n> For hidden in Stillness is death's own law.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, Chapter 9 (\"Chaand aur Taare\"), [translation](https://falsafa-corpus.com/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/09-chaand-aur-taare/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, Chapter 9 (\"Chaand aur Taare\"), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/09-chaand-aur-taare/translation/#p-6fe8f3).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, Chapter 9 (\"Chaand aur Taare\"), [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/09-chaand-aur-taare/translation/#p-e04f7c-p-fb94a9).",
